AB  - The growth and development of plants from most species is restricted by low temperature stress at some stage of their life cycle. To cope with this stress, plants have evolved adaptive mechanisms that are temperature regulated and involve acclimation processes that can be reversed. Survival of temperatures below freezing is normally the emphasis of discussions on breeding for low temperature tolerance in field crops. The selection for complex genetic traits such as low temperature tolerance, can be simplified in plant breeding programs when linked qualitative markers are identified. This method of locating quantitative trait loci requires a detailed marker gene linkage map and in many crop species there is a dearth of markers. In addition to providing sophisticated tools for more intensive studies to establish genetic potential at the chromosomal/DNA level, developments in molecular genetics have presented an opportunity to investigate expression of genetic potential at the RNA and polypeptide level. . © 1993 by the Crop Science Society of America, Inc. All Rights Reserved.
