TI  - A 3D thermo-mechanical model to study plate distortions during quenching process
AB  - Flatness defects such as edge waves, center buckles, longbows and crossbows are can easily be created during water cooling. The mechanism of flatness deterioration due to water cooling is not well understood. It causes operational trouble and can result in poor quality of product and productivity loss for repairing. ArcelorMittal Global R&D has developed a three dimensions finite element model to understand the link between cooling process and flatness. The model is developed to support the design of new quench investments and to improve the quench practices. The 3D model developed with Abaqus is able to predict the evolution of plate temperature, thermal stresses, strains, and distortions all along the cooling process. The cooling device is represented by top and bottom movable surfaces where a heat flux depending on width, length and temperature is applied. The effect of phase transformation is at first represented by a variation of thermal expansion coefficient. It is used to evaluate the effect of an unsymmetrical cooling along various directions. The first results show that the shape obtained by the model is comparable to real shape plate. Final distortion for thick and thin plates is presented. The effect of platen rolls is also commented.
