VL  - 1
SP  - 798-804
AB  - This paper presents the status of a thorium mixed oxide fuel (Th-MOX) development and irradiation campaign, which is being conducted by Thor Energy, a Norwegian cooperation supported by a consortium of industrial and R&D institutions. The objective of the campaign is to support claims that thorium (Th) provides a comparative advantage if used as the major fertile component in nuclear fuel for conventional light water reactors. The scope of the project is focused around PuO2-ThO2 and UO2-ThO2 ceramics to address fuel manufacturing, fuel cycle neutronics and economics, and in-pile thermal and mechanical behavior. Thorium, as the basis fertile component for a mixed oxide fuel, is advantageous for many reasons. The combination of plutonium and thorium to form a Th-MOX fuel is an attractive way to incinerate reactor or weapons grade plutonium. The irradiation of Th-MOX results in a spent reactor fuel with lower radiotoxicity and plutonium levels. Furthermore, thorium oxide is highly inert and cannot be oxidized beyond its +4 oxidation state (unlike UO2 which easily oxidizes to U308). ThO2 is also much less soluble in aqueous media. As a result of the aforementioned, ThO2 provides safety benefits in abnormal reactor operation and added safety margins in waste management and spent fuel storage. ThO2 has a higher thermal conductivity and releases less fission gas due to a higher degree of oxide stability than UO2. The higher absorption cross-section and the reduced fast fission factor of Th coupled with the flatter spectrum dependent neutron yield of uranium-233 allows more plutonium to be loaded into the fuel pins while still maintaining adequate safety margins and negative reactivity coefficients. Lastly, the net plutonium destruction for thorium-based fuels is roughly 50 - 70 percent, vastly exceeding that of uranium based fuels. The Norwegian Th-MOX program began by detailing manufacturing blueprints for these fuel ceramics. Care was taken to insure that sufficient uniformity and high theoretical density were achieved in a simple process compatible with current commercial LWR fuel manufacturing. The irradiation test is being conducted at the Halden reactor operated by the Norwegian Institute of Energy Technology (IFE). A highly instrumented test rig has been configured to take on-line measurements of fission gas release, fuel stack elongation, cladding elongation, fuel pellet swelling, pellet cladding mechanical interaction, neutron flux environment, fuel temperature profile, coolant flow and coolant temperatures. Following the irradiation the fuel will be subjected to post irradiation analysis to examine fission gas composition, fuel microstructure evolution, thermal conductivity evolution and other fuel matrix properties. The data collected from the campaign is aimed to demonstrate not only the advantages, but also the safe and long-term reliable performance of Th-MOX. This data will directly support the planning and approval of a commercial irradiation of such fuel.
