AB  - Temperature is a critical factor that influences the distribution and abundance of animals such as fish. Temperature has these effects at the population and community level because of its effects on processes at the chemical and biochemical levels of organization. Temperature influences the rates at which chemical and biochemical reactions proceed. Temperature also affects the formation and stabilization of weak bonds, which affect the structure and function of DNA, RNA, proteins, and membranes. Together, these physico-chemical effects at the molecular level alter the function of processes at higher levels of biological organization and influence whole-organism performance and fitness. Fishes use a variety of strategies to avoid or mitigate these effects of temperature both on short timescales (behavioral avoidance, biochemical and physiological acclimation) and on long (evolutionary) timescales through the evolution of differing thermal strategies. © 2011 Elsevier Inc. All rights reserved.
